==English==

===Phrasal verb===
{{en-infl-verb|inf=to [[kid]] on the [[square]]|kids on the square|kidding on the square|kidded on the square}}

# to be joking, but at the same time really mean it.

The phrase was popularized by [[Al Franken]] in his book ''[[Lies and the Lying Liars Who Tell Them]]'' when he describes the negative reaction of [[Paul Wolfowitz]] to one of his jokes. However, it was in use many years prior to Franken's book. The [[Raquel Welch]] movie ''Fathom'' ([[1967]]) [http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0061653/] used the phrase 36 years earlier. A character joked that Fathom was "kidding on the square."